Troubadour & trouvere song
  Most significant body of vernacular song in the Middle Ages.
  Troubadours - S France; Trouveres - N France
  Begain in S in 12th cent. and spread N
  Cultivated in courts and cities under aristocratic sponsorship
  Subjects - mostly courtly love, though some on political, moral, litrary topics.

Analyzing songs: TMRC
  Text: subject of the songs
  Music: musical features
  how do the words and music *Relate*
  Context: Who would perform the music and in what setting?

The mardrigal
  Aristocratic form of poetry and music, from Italy, hitting England and France
  4-6 voices, for amateurs
  emotional expressions of weeping, sighing, trembing, dying
  word-painting
  unsatisfied desire

The chanson
  During Francis (1515 - 1547), composers in France developed new type of chanson.
  Light, fast, strongly rhythmic song for four voices.
  Pleasant, amorous situations, though more serious texts were occasioally chosen.
  In simple forms, text set syllabically, duple meter.
  Amateurs.
  Word-painting.
